er trial factoring.

I don't think this will be a problem, so long as you use a bounded cache with LRU eviction. The cache would need to be designed so that an cache "hit" happens whenever a prime factor is actually present in some input to `factorint`. Random primes that are never seen again would be evicted and primes that are seen often would stay in the cache.

There are also other eviction strategies that might be more appropriate. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cache_replacement_policies For instance, maybe LFU (least frequently used) would make more sense than LRU. Or maybe something else. There's a ton of literature here. The main thing is to test this against some real world usage (speaking of which, do we know of actual real uses where this is a problem at all? Most code does not involve very large numbers). ","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sympy/sympy/issues/comments/2433497081/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

